Subject The Wedding, and a Poem~
Text
* A small parchment is folded into a square. On the outside,
\#To Pikkli\# is written in  smooth, graceful lettering. *
  
Dearest Pik,

In thinking about the wedding, I realized that if we plan a
large and formal ceremony, the chances of us being interrupted
by Guardians are high.  It\@d be a pity to have the ceremony
erupt into chaos, the groom and best man suddenly fighting
for their life--and all the guests becoming outlawed as well
as they help.  I hate to even think about such a scene.

Do you think, that given our circumstances, we should opt
for something small, something quiet?  Perhaps even unannounced?
I think it may be best.  If you don\@t, I quite understand--after
all, we\@ll have only one wedding, and family and friends
should ideally be a part.  Please give it some thought.

You know, though, there is a good deal of romance to the idea
of a secret wedding with outlaws and all--the stories we could
tell when we are older!  And, I must admit, I wouldn\@t mind avoiding
the planning and arranging of a big ceremony.  But most of all,
I should admit that I\@m eager to look at you from over the
pool, and this time promise my love forever--and be your
husband.  Forgive my impatience!
   
To wait and to anticipate your love
After long months or seeming years had passed
Was bitter sweetness, like a mystic trove
Where dazzling, ward-enchanted gems are massed.
I could not touch your hand but in my dream,
Nor see your gentle smile but in my mind,
The ache of missing you a constant theme
Despite the signs that showed our fates aligned.
Together through a spirit-bond of hope
Though distances and sunsets do us part,
The simple magics of the heart are rope
That bind us more than any mystic\@s art.
  I cannot touch my dreams unless with you,
  And so my heart and hopes will remain true.
   
Love you,
Jrihi
~
