Subject *sacrificed*~
Text
*A heavy card of vellum, several feet wide, is framed with dark
cherrywood, polished smooth.  Strong watercolors have been used to paint an
unsettling scene, the color combinations pointedly off-kilter just enough to
confuse and disorient the eye.  A twisted, nonlinear perspective has been
used, making the entire painting seem....  Twisted, wrenched out of
alignment with reality.  

You see before you the top of a tall, solid pyramid, hefty blocks of hewn
reddish stone as tall as an alatharya stacked to the sky.  The top is flat,
roughly twenty paces square.  Upon it is a great golden Altar, the paint
shimmering magically.  Great arcs of blue-white lightning are flashing from
the radiant crystal orb atop the glowing Altar, a traditional revivalist
symbol of the ancient One Magic.  

A circle of yai\@alya, clad in gleaming robes woven of platinum, gold, and
mei\@tzec, ring the Altar in.  Some heads are bowed in respect, but many more
are lifted heavenward, chins tilted upward in defiant stares.  The
mind-wrenching perspective becomes acutely visible as your eyes follow the
line of sight of the ringed figures, the lines perfectly straight, yet
not-straight.  

The sky, a peaceful blue spotted with light clouds, glows with a soft light
that seems out of place with the rest of the discord central to the
painting.  However, the sky just above the vividly-portrayed orb, energy
almost tangibly crackling through the air around it, becomes a livid, dull
purple, a bank of clouds throbbing with an unhealthy, bruised light born of
an ancient and powerful wrath.  The disturbingly power-laden light is
reflected in the eyes of the circle of the yai\@alya, as the figures seem
tensed, anticipating yet not knowing what doom they have summoned upon
themselves.  

Below and far away, faintly visible in the background, rifts and rents have
begun to radiate outwards from the unseen base of the titanic pyramid.  

A small signature is inked in the corner: \@Pikkli\@.  A simple, carven legend
reads at the bottom of the frame: \@The Vanity of the Yai\@Alya\@.  * 
