Subject \#Ignorance is bliss.\#~
Text
As I travel the land of Avendar, I find many people knowingly, though
most times unknowingly following the titled mantra.  Such people are happy
to quickly judge others on their appearance, ethos, or alignment without
ever taking the time to research or analyze the situation.  Victims of
ignorant acts against them are not so simplistic or one- dimensional, and if
the perpetrators could lift up the veil clouding their intentions to see the
complexity of a person, mankind would benefit greatly.  The world must learn
that ignorance is not bliss, but rather a malevolent whirlpool spinning,
confusing, and dragging us down into the depths of ill-fated prejudice. 
Although guardians are not perfect by any means, their actions within town
are a steadfast example of how we might propel ourselves into a more
accepting and pleasant future.  

The first of my observations starts with the induction of Ssillisan into the
guardian ranks.  I heard a big uproar from the masses on how a srryn could
ever become a protector of the law, for srryns are stereotyped as
destructive and having a lack of discretion.  Yet, that is just what it is,
a stereotype.  Those who blindly buy into it find themselves hating
Ssillisan without knowing his true story.  I have not made up my mind on the
whole matter, because I have not had a chance to speak with him on how he
became a guardian.  Yet, my brief encounter with him proved he was very
analytical himself.  It appeared one day he was attacked and killed by a
kankoran in town, then looted by someone.  He suspected the assassin
Ssthinkar, and asked me if I witnessed it, but when I did not, Ssillisan did
not jump to his suspected conclusion but rather went on with his ways. 
There was a silver lining though, for surely he gained the knowledge to be
wary of Ssthinkar, and such knowledge proves useful in the future.  

An instance of ignorance that is seen with ethos is also found upon the law
folk.  The fearsome, and much hated shuddeni guardian, Biezkul, seems to
cause much anger on the behalf of others who then direct their rage against
his companions.  I have heard many who walk the lighted path denounce all
guardians just by association with Biezkul, and I find it appalling.  The
likes of Jidriln and Kiiran are in fact good natured beings and do well in
upholding the law.  When Biezkul is on his Rveyelhi crusade to vanquish
those who are chaotic in nature, an act of ignorance in itself, one will not
find Jidriln nor Kiiran at his side.  To hate by association is flipped yet
equally alarming as believing stereotypes, for you are applying the ideals
of one to some.  Those like Jidriln do not care if someone is chaotic,
lawful, evil, or good, just as long as he or she does not break the laws
while in town.  And even if a law is broken, he must interrogate two
witnesses in order to validate the story before he can act upon it.  The
research that is involved before marking someone as criminal is a small step
in the right direction for everyone to use in making judgments upon others. 


As stated before, guardians are not perfect, and Biezkul proves such.  As a
follower of Rveyelhi, he is sanctioned to hunt down all those who are
chaotic in nature, granted they are outside of town, and put them to rest. 
It is hard to believe that all those who are chaotic cannot and will not
live peacefully within or alongside a civilization.  They may not like it,
but that doesn\@t mean they are actively trying to destroy it.  Not to be
outdone, those chaotic followers of Girikha are willed to hunt down all
guardians.  The Windwolf and her followers believe that all forms of law
prevent the spirit of freedom and impose tyrannical shackles upon all.  Yet,
who is to say that a guardian cannot love the freedom that nature provides
outside the city, and also protect those who reside within?  I have not seen
signs of expansion of the city with my own eyes or the destruction of the
forests by those of the law.  There is a preconceived notion that
civilization and nature cannot co-exist, but can we not turn to the Pack and
see it exist within that?  Even their society has some type of order.  It is
another testament to the guardians that all creatures, evil or good, chaotic
or neutral can reside and be provided and protected by the city.  This
knowledge is out there in front of our very eyes, and yet there are so many
who are shrouded and act in either blind faith or ignorant bias.  

The whirlpool of prejudice spins faster these days, and many are sucked in
as their perceptions are distorted.  To judge and execute without knowledge
is what prevents this great land of Avendar from swimming free into a new
era.  An era that is more conducive for people having conversation and
relationships regardless of race, ethos, and alignment.  There will always
be conflict in the world, and battles must be fought, but destruction
without cause serves no purpose.  It only brings confusion, then revenge,
and most times neither party ever realizes how they plunged into a
continuous drama.  If more people took the initiative and patience to study
things we know, analyze what we gather, and research what is not yet found,
he or she could act without prejudice and set an example for others to
follow.  
~
